Instagram put this together, even put the music on it and asked if I wanted to post it as a reel. How could I say no? 

I have not performed since March 2020. I miss it so much 🥺🥰 so this was nice to see so many happy memories. Hoping to make my way back to performing soon :)

Hello! 
It's been awhile so I thought would share a recent practice clip :). While I still don't get to practice as much as I used to or would like, nevermind get the time (re: have the energy and be awake enough lol)  to review my practice videos  this was filmed within the last week, so the turn around time here on watching it and  getting it posted is something I can be proud of lol. 

Dancing here to Omar Khorsid's wonderful tribute to Oum Koulsoum's beautiful "Amal Hayati". 

I always found I struggled more slower paced pieces than faster paced ones, probably because being calm and present has not been a natural state for me, but it's one thing I felt I have gotten better at with motherhood, is learning to just be at ease with being in the moment and the pace that it is happening at. 

I hope you enjoy it :) Thank you for watching and for your continued support. 

If you would like to learn to dance with me you can join  me over on my Patreon page www.patreon.com/cassandrafoxdance where there are many tutorials, guided practices, some choreographies all for you to work through at your own decided pace. You can even learn to make a belt just like the one I am wearing and those videos are taught so you don't need any prior sewing experience :) 

Dress and belt made by me
Song is "Amal Hayati" by Omar Khorsid from his album "Tribute to Oum Koulsoum". 

🥰🥰

This was by far the hardest thing I have ever tried to do on my phone. Shout out to the people who edit videos/reels often because this felt way above my paygrade and skillset 🤣😆😂 I know the audio syncing isn't perfect at the start but I just ran out of time (cough*patience*cough) to try and get it right 🙈🙈

I have been working on my family's holiday outfits using this fabulous, festive, foxes jersey from @paapiidesign and thanks to colourblocking I was even able to squeeze out a little crop top for dance for me as well 😍🤩🥰 Hoping to share Felix and I'm matching outfits soon. 

Drum solo used is "Khatwet Serena" by Hossam Ramzy 
I used the "camilla" dress pattern by @soniaestepdesigns for the bodice for this crop top and then self drafted the flutter sleeves. 
Fun fact, I ran my sewing machine needle straight through the edge of my finger getting those sleeves shoved into it doing the burrito roll method. Worth it though. Finger is fine, machine is fine, pride is mostly healed 😅

Happy New Year!!! 

I feel like at this point being a bit belated is like just part of my brand/charm/dysfunction lol depending on how you look at it 🤣😂

I hope everyone enjoyed their holiday season and that their New Year is off to a good start 😊

2022 saw my son go from infant to toddler and I am really enjoying the toddler time (he just turned 17 months) 🥰🥰 I still find any attempt to achieve balance and more time for dancing very challenging but I am hopeful that it is something I will get better at this year :) 

I am so incredibly thankful for the kindness, support,and patience I have been shown. Sending out so much gratitude and love. 🥰

On a fun note, I realized that in 2022 I did not buy any clothing (aside from socks lol). Everything new I wore was something I had made myself :) One of my last makes of the year was this dress for the holidays. I love this stunning print by @fossandesign, which I got from @bibsandbootsfabric. I self drafted this pattern so it fits me just right, is very comfortable, and has a fully twirly skirt WITH pockets 😎😎

One of my goals last year was to get to a place where I make all of Felix's clothes or get them second hand, and I am thrilled to say that now his current wardrobe is made by me, except for his snow suits that I got second hand and some of his sleepers :) 

I feel fortunate that while I couldn't put the energy or time into dancing that I was used to, I was able to further develop my sewing skills. I am confident that this year I will get to a place where I can continue to work on both sewing and dancing while enjoying motherhood as well :) 

I hope you are perhaps inspired to return to or to try sewing and dancing (lol but not at the same time, that could get messy 😅)

Thank you Instagram for putting this together for me :) Such a nice montage of memories of my kitties. :) 

I know a couple of you have asked how the cats adapted to my son and they have all been amazing, in fact Carlene has claimed Felix as her person 🥰🥰 
Although they dance with me less because they seem to have decided to follow the general advice of "sleep when the baby sleeps" 🤣😂

Brrrr it's quite cold here this weekend. 
Luckily dancing is a great way to generate heat 😅
Have a few minutes? I encourage you to get up, follow along, and dance with me for 3 ish minutes. This is an intermediate level practice that focuses on maintaining consistency in movements, but I welcome any level to give it a go,  and modify movements and duration of movements as needed :) 

Enjoying moving, being aware of our breathing, our posture, and paying attention to how a move feels and if it feels consistent are what we want to focus on:) 

If you enjoyed this, you can find more like this on my Patreon in the Dance Drills and Thrills Tier :) 
If you enjoyed this but are more new to dancing I recommend the New to Dance Enthusiast Tier. If you want to do it all then the "Do All the Dancing Tier is for you". 
www.patreon.com/cassandrafoxdance

Plus you can learn to make a Fringetastic hip scarf just like the one I am wearing in this video. It's a super quick and fun project that is 100% beginner friendly and won't take more than a few hours. You can access that Tutorial in any of the dance tiers. 

Thank you for your continued kindness and support. ❤ I am so grateful that I am able to spread joy with dancing 🥰 

Song is "No Letting Go" by Wayne Wonder 

Top, leggings, bracelets and hip scarf made by me :) 
Top pattern is a modification of the bodice of the Camilla Dress by Sonia Estep Designs. Flutter sleeve is self drafted.

Drum solo is "El Genneyya" by Hossam Ramzy 

This February will be 15 years since I started dancing.

I used to look back at my early videos & cringe at the technical errors, spotty musicality, lack of control, lack of fitness/stamina etc, & just see everything that "could have been better" but now  I try to look at them with fondness. I choose to see the joy, excitement, ambition & sometimes even willful ignorance lol instead of JUST the areas the dancing could have been better. I am glad that girl all those years ago, saw those same errors but instead of just beating herself up over them, she showed up, she kept dancing & she let herself enjoy the process. She cried about it sometimes, but she always made her way back to sweating it out instead of just crying it out. 🤣😂 

I danced to a lot of drum solos with mediocrity before I started to dance to some well. My earliest costumes were loaded with "mistakes".  The first dress I ever made wouldn't stay up on my shoulders.  The 2nd one barely did lol. The fact that I did things that didn't work out how I wanted or imagined initially was just the first steps to learning to do them better. I often think of the things people give up on because they didn't get the expected result in the time they expected to get it in. So often we sell ourselves short instead of continuing to try & always learning as we go because we expect too much of ourselves too soon.  It's okay to do something badly, it's in fact one of the ways we improve. ❤❤ 

So I thought I would put forth a challenge I am doing myself & I invite you to join me. I am going to dance to same drum solo at the very least once a month for the entire year. I will film all my practices as I go so I can see the evolution of a years worth of input. I will be using "El Genneyya" by Hossam Ramzy but I enourage you to pick any song that you feel both inspires and challenges you :) 

You can learn to dance with me at www.patreon.com/cassandrafoxdance lots of tutorials and guides Practice videos to follow along with :) 

Thank you for your continued kindness and support.❤❤❤

Hello there! 

I was initially going to post and talk today about the continuous body shaming some of you insist on doing on social media which you apparently feel is justified because I am a dancer. But I honestly don't have the mental fortitude or energy for it today. I am also not about to let anything or anyone dampen my dance spirits or try to tarnish the unfiltered joy that music and dance bring me. Nor am I going to neglect to thank those who have been endlessly supportive and kind 💖  Thank you immensely. 😊 

So instead I am sharing this clip of some veil work practice. I found the patterns in this particular piece soothing and the colours of this veil by @silksbycelestina are just too beautiful to not admire. 

I was initially intimidated by veil work and put it off for as long as I could until I changed my perspective and tried seeing it as an extension of my body and another creative movement outlet for musicality, instead of just seeing it as a dance prop. Seeing it this way has really helped me over the years to dance WITH my veil:) 

Hope you enjoy the colours and patterns in this clip as well. You can learn to dance with me (including veil work) on my patreon page. Lots of tutorials and guided practices. You can also learn how to make a hip scarf like the one I am wearing in this video as I have a tutorial for that as well :) www.patreon.com/cassandrafoxdance 

Thank you and hope everyone enjoys their day❤
Song is "Aswan Dances" by M. Abdelfattah

It's a process and it's consistent practice over long periods of time that gets us there.

Happy International Dance Day! 

TLDR: Another long dance video and long caption. 😅🤣😉🤷‍♀️ 

Decided for International Dance Day I would share a favourite from one of my practice sessions back in March. 
I recently came across this live version of "Kolak Agebny" by Abdel Basset Hamouda and fell in love. He made me feel like I was there while it was being performed. I love it's energy, how it ebs and flows, and it's longer length. Initially in my earlier years, I was intimidated by longer songs, but the plot twist was I now love them. They give you the opportunity to really dig into the song and get creative and play. They help teach you to pace yourself and to be ever present in the moment. They remind you we really don't need to be in a rush. They help you develop your dancecraft and your stamina. 

In such a fast paced world and an internet full of short clips, some only seconds long, and how do you engage people with 1 song for 6.5 minutes? Truth is I don't expect to keep most engaged with a video like this, and I understand and appreciate many dont have the time or interest to watch a dance video of this length (which is very fair, no judgement or shame, I get it 😊❤) I'm sharing it today because it's a day to celebrate dance and I wanted to share a song that I enjoyed dancing to immensely. 

Thank you for being here, for your kindness and support and for reading. Hope you enjoy this video and are inspired to dance yourself. 💃🏻 

If you are "dance curious" and  want to learn to dance with me, you can find many classes, tutorials and folllw along practices on my patreon www.patreon.com/cassandrafoxdance
No prior dance experience required :)

While I didn't get a chance to post anything yesterday for International Belly Dance Day, I did get to some time to actually do some dancing, finally. It had been a couple weeks since I have been able to get a dedicated hour or so to actually practice. So I thought I would share some dancing that I did do on International Belly Dance Day on Mother's Day lol cause its the best I can do right now lol.

I think one of the biggest things I have I have felt deeply in new motherhood is that you simultaneously feel like you are trying to do it all, but feeling like you can't do it all, all whilst felling like that no matter what you do, you aren't doing enough. 😅😵‍💫

 It can be overwhelming and we can find ourselves feeling defeated more often than we would like. So as a reminder to others who can relate,  I know it doesn't feel like it a lot of the time but you are doing great❤

I am so grateful to be a mom and grateful for dance. Both help me to just enjoy the moment and be present. Both have helped me gain love and appreciation for my body, and both have helped me to grow as a person (and grow a person for that matter 🤣😅) 

So with that I wish you happy dancing, I wish you a peaceful and pleasant Mother's Day, and I wish you the capacity to show yourself some more kindness and grace as we navigate our lives. 
 
If you want to learn to dance with me, or learn to make a fringe belt like mine here, or just support my dancing,  there are many tutorials and guided practices on my patreon www.patreon.com/cassandrafoxdance

Thank you for reading 🥰

I finally finished 2 costumes that fit and here is one of them! 

I posted the full story of my path to getting new costumes made while trying to balance motherhood to a toddler and everything else on my Facebook page because Instagram thinks I am too long winded lol and would have cut off my caption. 

So Instagram gets the Cliff's Notes;
Since having my son my body has changed and none of my entire costume rotation (which I had all made myself) fit anymore. Even with conditioning now, it doesn't seem like the bras of my prior me-made costumes will ever fit again, although in good news it appears that the belts and skirts will.  Win some, lose some lol. 

It was really hard figuring out sizing for my new body especially with knowing making the costumes would take months and during those months I would be working on my dance conditioning. I had to guess end sizing and I guessed wrong and ended up with too big a belt and too small of a bra and had to entirely redo the bra and had to alter the belt. It was demoralizing, frustrating, and it just straight up made me sad. But I had to feel my feelings, pick myself back up and keep going, bit by bit. 

I feel such a sense of accomplishment now. I had doubted if I could even manage to do it but here I am now on the other side and I DID do it❤ 

In early months post partum I remember feeling so far from myself, so far from my goals, like I was adrift in a fog. In hindsight I wish I had of been kinder to myself in those early months and shown myself more patience. I was always going to get to where I was going it just might have been slower than I initially anticipated but thats the pace I needed for myself & my family and it's the pace that got me to where I am now. :) 

Thanks for reading :) You can learn to dance with me, step by step, slowly as you would like, on my Patreon www.patreon.com/cassandrafoxdance
You can also learn to slowly sew a super fun Fringe Belt on there (the belt tutorials are available on all 3 dance tiers). 

Have a great day😊 

#bellydance #drumsolo #dancecostume #sewing #postpartum

Hello. 
I am beyond heartbroken to share my dear cat Carlene, aka Queenie, is no longer with us. I am still struggling to find adequate words and still very much feeling consumed with grief. I feel like I have lost my familiar. 

I had Queenie since she was a bottle kitten that could fit in the palm of my hand. She was a wonderfully weird, & vibrant character, equal parts insistently independent and luxuriously loving. She was the spark of our household that just somehow seemed to bring everything to life. 

I was initially fostering her trying to find her a home but after 3 failed attempts it was clear to me I was keeping her and she was meant to be a part of my family. My other half often said she was just a cat version of me, or maybe I was just the human version of her. Whatever it was, we just got along. 

She welcomed my son Felix into our lives with so much love and care. I remember when it seemed like one day she just claimed him, as he was upset in his crib and I was there trying to sooth him and she just came trotting into the room, jumped into his crib and started purring up against him. He calmed right down. She genuinely seemed to enjoy his company and would soothe him, play with him, rest with him, and come for walks with us. 

I was asked often how I trained her to walk with us, and the truth was I never trained her to do anything. Whatever she did she did because she wanted to. She was simply given the chance and the love to be exactly who she was. And who she was just happened to be brilliant. She was so woven into our daily lives that its hard not to feel entirely unraveled by her absence. 

While no time would ever feel like enough, and I feel like we deserved far more time, I am profoundly grateful for the time that we did get, and that I was fortunate enough to know and love a cat like my Carlene. 
 
All my love my special girl, thanks for all the dances, and all the amazing memories ❤

Rest Well my Queenie ❤

Carlene "Queenie" Bean
March 2017 to June 2023

If you want to honour Carlene and are in a position to do so, please consider donating to your local cat shelter, like @furryfriendsshelter or adopting a cat in need of a home 💜

New Costume Reveal! 

It's always a beautiful moment for me to finally finish making a costume then get to take it for a proper test run. I admittedly don't love the entire process of making my own costumes because it's a lot of work, time, and money for quality materials. It's tedious and it doesn't always goes as planned, but the end result of getting to dance in something that I have designed and made to be what I wanted/needed for my dancing is well worth it to me in the end. It is a long game, like a lot of things. You only get to that end result by continuing to show up, even when you are struggling to. 

It has also helped further my appreciation and gave me expanded insight of what goes into making art in various mediums. 

And since someone always asks, I do not make costumes to sell and I don't see that ever changing. I don't know if I am a slow sewist (Maybe I am?!? I think I probably am) But my costumes usually take me an average of 40 hours minimum (some have been much longer, I am very bad at keeping track after a certain point), then factor in the cost of materials etc, there is no way anything I made would be "affordable", nevermind not having the time.  I will say I have never come across an "overpriced" bellydance costume. In fact compared to other dance genres bellydance costuming is typically wildly well priced for what you get. So if you have found a costume vendor you love,  remember to show your appreciation for their work. If you haven't found one you love yet, maybe thats a sign to try learning to make your own costumes yourself. You might not enjoy it, or you might find you really enjoy, but you won't know unless you try :) 

You can learn to dance with me (and also learn how to make a fabulous fringe belt and learn all about materials involved in costume makinv) on my patreon www.patreon.com/cassandrafoxdance 
All my tutorials are slow paced and thorough so you don't need prior experience in dance or sewing, you just need to be willing to try :) 

Thanks for the continued kindness and support. Hope you are all enjoying your weekend. ❤

Hello
I have been struggling to find any words, nevermind dance mojo as of late given both personal circumstances and the state of the world. It is with great sadness that I share that in October, my dear horse Shadow, at the very full age of 30, passed on.  

I had figured it was coming and had the vet booked for the start of November to evaluate him but Shadow, true to his character, decided it would be on his terms. I am sad I did not get the goodbye I imagined for us and that I was not there during his final moments. I've been coming to terms with the fact that the last time I saw him was our last moment. But even in my sadness I feel incredibly blessed and fortunate that we were able to spend 28 years of our lives together and that he lived a full and enjoyable life. 

Some of my happiest memories of my life, from early adolescence through to adulthood were shared with Shadow. We weren't grand winners or overly great at what we did, but we were grand partners and we had fun and worked together as a team. We learned to see each other just as we were and to find joy in our adventures. Shadow was one of my best friends and greatest teachers. He was a big goofy guy, and a genuinely kind horse. There were many times he took care of me, and stood by me while we figured things out. 

He loved being with his "herd" more than anything and always looked out for them. He was a wonderful, beautiful soul and it has been an absolute pleasure to be have been his human for almost 3 decades ❤️  You will be greatly missed and oh so fondly remembered  with deep love Shadow. Thank you for everything🥰🥲  Rest well. 

I am also deeply aware that in Palestine thousands of people are grieving their loved ones whose lives have been torn from them in horrendously violent ways, and the collective pain and grief is palpable. The decades of continued violence against the Palestinian people is inexcusable.

I know it can feel overwhelming with all the information online and trying to figure out what to do where to start, especially when it comes to things like boycotting brands to show your support of 🍉 🇵🇸 

I just wanted to say to you, do what you can and what is accessible to you and within your means. When it comes to collective efforts the idea is something, even if a small thing, is better than nothing. Share the information. If you can't do something fully, you can still try to just scale back. 

Years ago I wanted to step back from buying fast fashion and mass produced clothing due to not only its impact on the environment but to the human cost of the garment workers. This felt accessible to me because I had a sewing machine and an interest in learning how to make my own clothes. It was a goal to move towards making most if not all of my own clothing. But it would have been unrealistic to think I could just instantly transition to that. Its not by any means cheaper, its very time consuming, and it's definitely a learning process.  It took years for me to now say I do in fact make the large majority of my and Felix's clothing, as well as clothing for my partner as well. I try to upcycle and thrift where possible too. 

I'm not saying this to say "if I can do it so can you",  I'm saying this to illustrate we can a find ways that can work for us to make meaningful changes for cause(s) we care about.

The key is starting. We just have to start making those small changes. We can focus our efforts on the portion of a boycott or change that are accessible to us. Sewing/clothing might not be an area you can or want to focus on. Maybe for you it is beauty brands or foods etc. Maybe its all of the above. We aren't all playing the same hand of cards but we are all involved in the game. Make the most of the hand you are dealt in a way that can make a difference even if it seems small. Maybe you will watch this video and be inspired to try upcycling or sewing❤

As a child one of my favourite movies was The Secret of NIMH and honestly its still a favourite. 

I always loved the quote "Courage of the heart is very rare. The stone has a power when it's there". 

As I grew up I realized how true it is. The power was never just in the stone but rather in the heart of the one holding it. The power is in our voices, in our actions. We all have the capacity to create our own power and to decide how to use it.
Mrs Brisby, despite being a small, widowed field mouse risked everything to save her son, and to move her home to safe space for her family. She was brave, she was vulnerable, she was scared but she proceeded. She believed in a moment that the impossible could be possible.

While in these past 67 days we have seen the darkest aspects of humanity, we have seen our fellow humans endure a horrific level of violence, we have seen them suffer incredibly profound loss. We have felt our hearts shatter endlessly

But, We have also seen so much courage of the heart, especially from the people of Pal *es *tine. It is NOT rare in G❤A🖤Z🤍A💚 

We have seen people who have lost everything continue to do everything they can to help one another. We have seen them keep going when it seems like an impossibility. We have seen health care professionals risk their lives, and in fact sadly lose their lives in an effort to keep helping those who need it.  We have seen the Press continue to tell the story of their reality while holding their grief of seeing their colleagues and loved ones lives taken. 

We have seen people all over the world, across varying diverse communities raise their voices for the violence to end, and for freedom and peace to prevail, often knowing that it could be something they may be penalized for in their personal or professional lives. ❤ We have continually seen the power of courage of the heart when its there. 

Thank you to all of those who found theirs. May you please continue to spread it whenever you go.

Hello 💫
I hope everyone enjoyed their holidays, and if you don't celebrate anything I simply hope you were able to enjoy the end of the year. I know for many the holidays aren't necessarily an enjoyable time and I know given the many atrocities going on in the world a "happy holidays" was not even possible. Many have suffered through them and continue to do so.  Dualities are an uncomfortable reality in life, in any given moment you can have new life being welcomed and celebrated while others grieve a life and love just lost. One's best day can easily be another's worst day as the reality is we experience different things at different times. And while it is much easier said than done, we can always acknowledge and hold space for both. I can admit I myself have been struggling to do so. It is so hard to see what we see daily and not feel profoundly impacted by it. 

I do want us all to have a happy new year. I want us all to have a year full of beautiful things and times, a year full of making memories and sharing experiences. A year of softness and kindness for ourselves and others. A year of understanding that being strong doesn't mean being cruel.  A year of realizing you don't need to cultivate a "new" or "better" you because an immense amount of marketing and messaging told you you need to. A year where you can makes changes only because YOU wish to do so for yourself. A year where you can exist exactly as yourself ❤ 

I also want us to have a year of using our voices in whatever way is accessible to us to advocate for change. A year to see and remember we are all human. A year to reflect on how our choices not just impact us directly but also the world around us. A year where we take pause to consider the intent of our words and actions before we speak or act. A year where we appreciate how precious life is and remember that it is precious for most of us no matter how different we might seem on the surface. ❤ 

And hopefully may this be a year where we refuse to silently witness active genocides and displacements and where we see them end. ❤🖤🤍💚

With love and gratitude, 
Cassandra

Hi :) 
Thank you for all of the kind and supportive responses on my last few posts ❤ 

I wanted to share the last thing I made in 2023 & the first thing I made in 2024, which is the Lowland Patterns Half Zip Sweater @lowlandkids 

I made Felix's first & I was really excited about it. He is in his "Bee Era" 🐝 and it's a really beautiful privilege to get the opportunity to indulge your child's interest. He was so excited when we saw it & he loves wearing it. 
I did really struggle with the collar/zipper/bias tape lol. I ended up having to stitch rip several times & interface a bunch of pieces after the fact. Despite the seams not lining up at all (lol) the zipper somehow did and it's very wearable so it turned out to be a great learning curve. 😀 

I started mine a day or so after Felix's determined to do a better job on the collar section & bias tape. I have learned that if I struggle with something I need to attempt it again shortly after because if I wait to long my brain apparently can't locate the file with the lesson I supposedly learned 🤣😅 

I tried sewing a lot of new things last year & have gotten better at enjoying the process versus being disappointed in my results. Progress takes time and there is nothing that says you can't make it a priority to enjoy said time versus trying to improve as quickly as possible. This applies to all hobbies, jobs, interests,  & skills I think. 
It's okay to mess up. It's okay to make imperfect things. It's okay to be proud of imperfect makes. And most of all its okay to do things simply because we enjoy them ❤
